name: Allá en el Rancho Grande
comments: Written in the 1920s for a musical play, but now most commonly associated with the eponymous 1936 Mexican motion picture "Allá en el Rancho Grande". There has been a vigorous debate about who actually wrote the song. Some say nobody can take credit for the composition because the authorship is unknown. The tune was around long before it had any commercial success, the argument goes, and is simply a folk song that’s now in the public domain. Nevertheless, prominent songwriters on both sides of the US-Mexican border have claimed the song's copyrights. The most widely accepted credit is by Juan Díaz del Moral, for the lyrics, and Emilio D. Uranga, for the music. The song was originally written for Mexico City’s vibrant musical theater, according to Diaz del Moral’s biography on the website of SACM, the Mexican composer’s society. The pair reportedly registered the song in 1927, nine years before the film was released.

name: Fond Affection
comments: Also known as "The Broken Heart", "Go and Leave Me If You Wish To". Closely related to The Dear Companion Gavin Greig found that it was popular in Aberdeenshire at the turn of the century, where he collected a version that was published in the newspaper The Buchan Observer. There were many requests for it via the newspaper. In 1906, after they’d collected a number of versions in the North-East, Greig remarked that “the song has been traditional [in Scotland] for a while” Also collected in 1909 by H.M. Belden for the Missouri Folk-Lore Society. Here are the lyrics of the version by The Carter Family Once I loved your fond affection all my hopes on you was spent till a dark eyed girl persuaded and you cared no more for me Go on and leave me if you wish to never let me cross your mind, In your heart you love another never on earth will I call you mine

name: Oh Happy Day, That Fixed My Choice
comments: The verses come from Doddridg's hymn "Rejoicing in Our Covenant Engagement to God". The refrain (Oh Happy Day, Oh Happy Day, when Jesus washed my sins away! He taught me how to watch and pray, and live rejoicing every day.) which was not part of Doddridge's hymn, but was added in 1854, seems to have been adapted from a secular song, "Happy Land, Whate'er My Fate in Life May Be", that was either written or arranged by Rimbault.

name: Old Blue
